'''Sir Joseph Robert Archibald Glenn''', [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (24 May 1911{{spaced ndash}}4 January 2012) was an Australian industrialist and founding [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[La Trobe University]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Vale: Sir Archibald Glenn, OBE |url=https://www.latrobe.edu.au/news/articles/2012/article/vale-sir-archibald-glenn,-obe |publisher=[[La Trobe University]] |date=10 January 2012 |access-date=17 April 2018 }}</ref><ref name=administration>{{cite web |title=Past Chancellors and Vice-Chancellors |url=https://www.latrobe.edu.au/about/at-a-glance/history |work=Our history |publisher=[[La Trobe University]] |date=16 March 2018 |access-date=17 April 2018 }}</ref>

==Biography==
Glenn was born in 1911<ref>[http://www.scotch.vic.edu.au/Gscot/GSdec04/48arch.htm Scotch College: Great Scot]</ref> and raised near [[Sale, Victoria]].<ref name=obit>David Balderstone, obituary: "Helped set up unis, headed ICI", ''The Age'', 28 January 2012, p. 27</ref> He was educated at [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], where he moved after Sale High School found itself without a mathematics teacher.<ref name=obit/>  He studied engineering at the [[University of Melbourne]] and later in London. He joined ICI (Imperial Chemical Industries Australia, now known as [[Orica]]) where he became managing director for 25 years,retiring in 1973, and where he was Chairman for 10 years. During World War II he worked alongside [[Essington Lewis]], who was in charge of war-related industry as Director-General of the [[Department of Munitions]].<ref name=obit/>

He was Chairman of the Scotch College Council from 1963 to 1981, and [[Ormond College]] Council from 1976 to 1981.<ref name=obit/>

He was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1965<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1109176&search_type=simple&showInd=true It's an Honour: OBE]</ref> and was knighted in 1966.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1083539&search_type=simple&showInd=true It's an Honour: Knight Bachelor]</ref> He died on 4 January 2012, aged 100.<ref name="Obituary">{{cite news|title=Sir Archibald Glenn |newspaper=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]] |date=2012-01-07 |url=http://tributes.heraldsun.com.au/obituaries/heraldsun-au/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=155350647 |accessdate=2012-01-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120717105735/http://tributes.heraldsun.com.au/obituaries/heraldsun-au/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=155350647 |archivedate=17 July 2012 }}</ref>

His first wife was Elizabeth "Betty" née Balderstone, whom he married in 1939.  After Betty died in 1988, he married Sue Debenham. His four children included [[Di Gribble]], editor, publisher and deputy chair of the ABC;<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KWfSljNdE4oC&pg=PA351 Kenneth Stanley Inglis, Whose ABC?: The Australian Broadcasting Corporation, 1983–2006]</ref> she predeceased him by three months.<ref name=obit/>

